who commissioned, built, and lived in these buildings. Almost all of these architects, both Europeans and non-Europeans, have remained unknown beyond – at best – their surnames. Through extensive archival research, this book reconstructs their lives, providing vital background for the buildings themselves. Much more than in the French empire of the Western Hemisphere, the buildings in this book adapt to indigenous styles, regardless of whether they were designed and built by European or non-European architects.The Architecture of Empire provides a unique, comprehensive study of structures that rank among the most fascinating examples of intercultural exchange in the history of global empires.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  aAsian.  aAssociationism.  aAyutthaya.  aBangkok.  aBeaux-Arts.  aBelle Epoque.  aBurma.  aCambodia.  aCarnatic Wars.  aCompagnie Indes.  aEcole Superieure.  aExtreme-Orient.  aFrance.  aFrench.  aHaiphong.  aHanoi.  aJean-Baptiste Colbert.  aLaos.  aLouis XIV.  aLuang Prabang.  aOrientales.  aParis.  aPhnom Penh.  aSaigon.  aSecond.  aSiam.  aThailand.  aThird Republic.  aVietnam.  aancien regime.  acolonialism.  afrancaise.  ahybridity.  ametissage.  amuseums.  aopera houses.  atheatres.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228012443?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228012443423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228012443/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles